the state
of local investigative reporting
today and

47:32.116 --> 47:33.718 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
its future."

47:33.751 --> 47:36.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What -- you thought that even as
you were
watching the movie. What was
troubling?

47:36.687 --> 47:40.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET SULLIVAN, The New York
Times: Well,
it's very troubling to me,
because I'm a former

47:40.291 --> 47:45.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
editor of a regional newspaper,
and I watch
these issues carefully.

47:45.396 --> 47:51.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Staff numbers are way down. Many
papers have
to or have felt they have had to
dismantle

47:51.902 --> 47:56.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their investigative teams. And
the resources
just aren't there that were
there even 10

47:56.707 --> 47:58.509 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
years ago. It's really
troubling.

47:58.542 --> 48:04.115 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, Steve
Engelberg, the economics
of the business are clearly one
issue. What

48:04.148 --> 48:07.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
