reporting tools we have ever had
in the Internet.

48:16.227 --> 48:20.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's amazing what we can now
access in terms
of information. And people are
reading more.

48:20.965 --> 48:25.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The problem we have got is that
people aren't
willing to pay for it. And
that's a big problem.

48:25.736 --> 48:29.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as Margaret says, it's a
particularly
acute problem outside the major
cities of

48:29.907 --> 48:34.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the United States, and even in
some of those
major cities, where newspapers
are at 50 percent

48:34.845 --> 48:39.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or less of their previous size.
That's the
problem. It's an economic
problem.

48:39.183 --> 48:42.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From the perspective of the
craft, it's a
great time to be an
investigative reporter.

48:42.586 --> 48:45.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But flesh that
out a little
bit. So, it's really a
double-edged sword

48:45.923 --> 48:51.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of technology, right, about
digital technology
allows a certain kind of more
reporting and

48:51.662 --> 48:55.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more dissemination, but you're
saying the
economics make it harder.

48:55.065 --> 48:58.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN ENGELBERG: Exactly,
because people
feel on the Internet that
content ought to

48:58.302 --> 49:00.237 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
